~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~~âœ¨ Basics on Forms âœ¨---
â€¢â€¢Simple Buttonâ€¢â€¢
<input type="submit" value="Submit Form">
<button type="submit">Submit Form</button>

â€¢â€¢The attributes of the <form> element sets the HTTP method.â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢The <form>'s action and method attributes define the URL which processes the form data & the HTTP method used to submit the data.â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢ You can set the <action> to determine where your data can be sent.â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢If a <form method="dialog"> is inside a <dialog>, submitting this form will close the dialog.Howevwr this is the recommended method
<formmethod="dialog"> & <formnovalidate> on the submit button.â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢When a button includes a {formaction, formenctype, formmethod, formnovalidate, & formtarget attribute}, the value that is set on the button, activating the form submission will take precedence over the {action, enctype, method,& target} set on that <form>.â€¢â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢Method Exampleâ€¢â€¢
<form method="GET">
  <label for="student">Pick a student:</label>
  <select name="student" id="student">
    <option value="daily">Daily Investors</option>
    <option>Guardian Angel</option>
    <option value="art">Artificial Intelligence</option>
  </select>
  <input type="submit" value="Submit Form">
</form>


â€¢â€¢ When using "<input> elements" to where the user can't edit the value. You should always include a value, that includes the input elements with a type of {hidden, radio, checkbox, submit, button, and reset tag}
